{{Infobox mountain | name = Mount Aonomine | image = [[File:Mt. Aonomine from Shimonogo, Isobe.jpg|250px]] | caption = View from the Shima City side | elevation_m = 336.3 | coordinates = {{coord|34|24|32|N|136|49|27|E|type:mountain|display=inline,title}} | location = {{JPN}} [[Mie Prefecture]] ([[Toba City]] and [[Shima City]]) | range = Isolated mountain | type = Low-altitude, solitary mountain<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.23</ref> }} '''Mount Aonomine''' (青峰山, Aonomine-san<ref>Mie Prefecture (2005) "[http://www.pref.mie.jp/KAWASABO/HP/kasen/seibi/kamokihon.pdf Basic Policy for River Improvement in the Kamo River System]" p.3</ref>) is a mountain located on the border between {{ill|Toba City|ja|鳥羽市}} and {{ill|Shima City|ja|志摩市}} in {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県}}. It has an elevation of 336 meters. == Overview == Despite its relatively low elevation, Mount Aonomine offers clear views of {{ill|Ise Bay|ja|伊勢湾}}, {{ill|Enshū-nada Sea|ja|遠州灘}}, and {{ill|Kumano-nada Sea|ja|熊野灘}}, making it a landmark for {{ill|kaisen|ja|廻船}} sailors in ancient times. The mountain is home to {{ill|Shofuku-ji Temple|ja|正福寺 (鳥羽市)}}, which enshrines a golden statue of {{ill|Kannon|ja|観音}} riding on a {{ill|whale|ja|鯨}}. The temple has historically been a site for maritime safety prayers. The mountain’s forests of {{ill|Castanopsis|ja|シイ}} and {{ill|Quercus|ja|カシ}} trees contribute to its scenic beauty, making it a popular spot on the {{ill|Kinki Nature Trail|ja|近畿自然歩道}}. While the advent of GPS has reduced its significance as a navigational aid, the area is preserved as a {{ill|Protective Forest for Navigation|ja|航行目標保安林}}. The summit features an observation deck and a digital television relay station, the {{ill|Isobe Relay Station|ja|磯部中継局}}. The haiku pen name of {{ill|Seihō Shimada|ja|嶋田青峰}}, a poet from nearby Matoya, is derived from this mountain.<ref>Hosoi (1996): p.48</ref> On May 25, 2016, Canadian Prime Minister {{ill|Justin Trudeau|en}} and his wife {{ill|Sophie Grégoire Trudeau|en}} hiked Mount Aonomine during their visit for the {{ill|42nd G7 Summit|en|第42回先進国首脳会議}} in Ise-Shima.<ref>"Canadian Prime Minister Enjoys Hiking with His Wife on Their Wedding Anniversary," *Chunichi Shimbun*, May 26, 2016</ref> == Geography and Geology == Mount Aonomine is classified as part of the "Eastern Terrace District," a 100–115 meter hilly region within Toba City.<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.18</ref> It serves as the source of the {{ill|Kamo River (Mie Prefecture)|ja|加茂川}}, a secondary river.<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.20</ref> Geologically, it belongs to the {{ill|Matoya Formation|ja|的矢層群}}, which is part of the {{ill|Shimanto Belt|ja|四万十層群}}, formed during the {{ill|Mesozoic Era|ja|中生代}}.<ref>Kawai (1967): p.44</ref> == Aonomine Trails == The mountain has several trails collectively known as "Aonomine Trails": * '''Matsuo Trail''': Two routes (old and new) starting from Matsuo in Toba City. * '''Kenko Trail''': A route starting in Kenko in Toba City. * '''Isobe Trail''': Starting from Izawa-no-Miya Shrine in Shima City. * '''Matoya Trail''': A drivable route from Matoya Shrine in Shima City. * '''Gochi Trail''': A pedestrian-only route starting near {{ill|Gochi Station|ja|五知駅}} in Shima City. == References == {{reflist}} == Further Reading == * Isobe Town History Compilation Committee, *Isobe Town History: Upper Volume*, 1997. * Kawai Masatora, "Exploring the Origins of the Japanese Archipelago," *Geological News*, 1967. * Toba City History Compilation Office, *Toba City History: Upper and Lower Volumes*, 1991. * Hosoi Keiji, "Seihō Shimada and the Haiku Literary Movement," *Haiku Literature Quarterly*, 1996. * Mie Prefecture Board of Education, *Historical Pathways of Ise: Asama-Toba Road and Others*, 1986. == Related Articles == * {{ill|Ise-Shima National Park|ja|伊勢志摩国立公園}} * {{ill|Navigation|ja|航路}} * {{ill|Landmarks|ja|航路標識}} * {{ill|Hiking|ja|ハイキング}} * {{ill|Hiyoriyama (Toba City)|ja|日和山 (鳥羽市)}} == External Links == * [http://maikoh.net/corp/event/aominezan/ Shofuku-ji Temple - Aonomine Mountain Official Page]
