Despite its relatively low elevation, Mount Aonomine offers clear views of {{ill|Ise Bay|ja|伊勢湾|12=draft}}, {{ill|Enshū-nada Sea|ja|遠州灘|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kumano-nada Sea|ja|熊野灘|12=draft}}, making it a landmark for {{ill|kaisen|ja|廻船|12=draft}} sailors in ancient times. The mountain is home to {{ill|Shofuku-ji Temple|ja|正福寺 (鳥羽市)|12=draft}}, which enshrines a golden statue of {{ill|Kannon|ja|観音|12=draft}} riding on a {{ill|whale|ja|鯨|12=draft}}. The temple has historically been a site for maritime safety prayers.
The mountain’s forests of {{ill|Castanopsis|ja|シイ|12=draft}} and {{ill|Quercus|ja|カシ|12=draft}} trees contribute to its scenic beauty, making it a popular spot on the {{ill|Kinki Nature Trail|ja|近畿自然歩道|12=draft}}. While the advent of GPS has reduced its significance as a navigational aid, the area is preserved as a {{ill|Protective Forest for Navigation|ja|航行目標保安林|12=draft}}. The summit features an observation deck and a digital television relay station, the {{ill|Isobe Relay Station|ja|磯部中継局|12=draft}}.
The haiku pen name of {{ill|Seihō Shimada|ja|嶋田青峰|12=draft}}, a poet from nearby Matoya, is derived from this mountain.<ref>Hosoi (1996): p.48</ref> On May 25, 2016, Canadian Prime Minister {{ill|Justin Trudeau|en}} and his wife {{ill|Sophie Grégoire Trudeau|en|12=draft}} hiked Mount Aonomine during their visit for the {{ill|42nd G7 Summit|en|第42回先進国首脳会議|12=draft}} in Ise-Shima.<ref>"Canadian Prime Minister Enjoys Hiking with His Wife on Their Wedding Anniversary," *Chunichi Shimbun*, May 26, 2016</ref> 
== Geography and Geology ==
Mount Aonomine is classified as part of the "Eastern Terrace District," a 100–115 meter hilly region within Toba City.<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.18</ref> It serves as the source of the {{ill|Kamo River (Mie Prefecture)|ja|加茂川|12=draft}}, a secondary river.<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.20</ref> Geologically, it belongs to the {{ill|Matoya Formation|ja|的矢層群|12=draft}}, which is part of the {{ill|Shimanto Belt|ja|四万十層群|12=draft}}, formed during the {{ill|Mesozoic Era|ja|中生代|12=draft}}.<ref>Kawai (1967): p.44</ref>
== Aonomine Trails ==
The mountain has several trails collectively known as "Aonomine Trails":
* '''Matsuo Trail''': Two routes (old and new) starting from Matsuo in Toba City.
* '''Kenko Trail''': A route starting in Kenko in Toba City.
* '''Isobe Trail''': Starting from Izawa-no-Miya Shrine in Shima City.
* '''Matoya Trail''': A drivable route from Matoya Shrine in Shima City.
* '''Gochi Trail''': A pedestrian-only route starting near {{ill|Gochi Station|ja|五知駅|12=draft}} in Shima City.
