[[sn:Aohou Mountain]]
[[en:Aohou Mountain]]
[[ja:青峰山]]

{{Infobox mountain
| name = Mount Aonomine
| image = [[File:Mt. Aonomine from Shimonogo, Isobe.jpg|250px]]
| caption = View from the Shima City side
| elevation_m = 336.3
| coordinates = {{coord|34|24|32|N|136|49|27|E|type:mountain|display=inline,title|qq=}}
| location = {{JPN|qq=}} [[Mie Prefecture]] ([[Toba City]] and [[Shima City]])
| range = Isolated mountain
| type = Low-altitude, solitary mountain<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.23</ref>
}}
'''Mount Aonomine''' (青峰山, Aonomine-san<ref>Mie Prefecture (2005) "[http://www.pref.mie.jp/KAWASABO/HP/kasen/seibi/kamokihon.pdf Basic Policy for River Improvement in the Kamo River System]" p.3</ref>) is a mountain located on the border between {{ill|Toba City|ja|鳥羽市|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shima City|ja|志摩市|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. It has an elevation of 336 meters.
== Overview ==
Despite its relatively low elevation, Mount Aonomine offers clear views of {{ill|Ise Bay|ja|伊勢湾|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Enshū-nada Sea|ja|遠州灘|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Kumano-nada Sea|ja|熊野灘|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, making it a landmark for {{ill|kaisen|ja|廻船|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} sailors in ancient times. The mountain is home to {{ill|Shofuku-ji Temple|ja|正福寺 (鳥羽市)|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, which enshrines a golden statue of {{ill|Kannon|ja|観音|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} riding on a {{ill|whale|ja|鯨|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. The temple has historically been a site for maritime safety prayers.
The mountain’s forests of {{ill|Castanopsis|ja|シイ|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Quercus|ja|カシ|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} trees contribute to its scenic beauty, making it a popular spot on the {{ill|Kinki Nature Trail|ja|近畿自然歩道|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. While the advent of GPS has reduced its significance as a navigational aid, the area is preserved as a {{ill|Protective Forest for Navigation|ja|航行目標保安林|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. The summit features an observation deck and a digital television relay station, the {{ill|Isobe Relay Station|ja|磯部中継局|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The haiku pen name of {{ill|Seihō Shimada|ja|嶋田青峰|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, a poet from nearby Matoya, is derived from this mountain.<ref>Hosoi (1996): p.48</ref> On May 25, 2016, Canadian Prime Minister {{ill|Justin Trudeau|en|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and his wife {{ill|Sophie Grégoire Trudeau|en|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} hiked Mount Aonomine during their visit for the {{ill|42nd G7 Summit|en|第42回先進国首脳会議|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in Ise-Shima.<ref>"Canadian Prime Minister Enjoys Hiking with His Wife on Their Wedding Anniversary," *Chunichi Shimbun*, May 26, 2016</ref> 
== Geography and Geology ==
Mount Aonomine is classified as part of the "Eastern Terrace District," a 100–115 meter hilly region within Toba City.<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.18</ref> It serves as the source of the {{ill|Kamo River (Mie Prefecture)|ja|加茂川|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, a secondary river.<ref>Toba City History Compilation Office (1991): Upper Volume, p.20</ref> Geologically, it belongs to the {{ill|Matoya Formation|ja|的矢層群|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, which is part of the {{ill|Shimanto Belt|ja|四万十層群|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, formed during the {{ill|Mesozoic Era|ja|中生代|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>Kawai (1967): p.44</ref>
== Aonomine Trails ==
The mountain has several trails collectively known as "Aonomine Trails":
* '''Matsuo Trail''': Two routes (old and new) starting from Matsuo in Toba City.
* '''Kenko Trail''': A route starting in Kenko in Toba City.
* '''Isobe Trail''': Starting from Izawa-no-Miya Shrine in Shima City.
* '''Matoya Trail''': A drivable route from Matoya Shrine in Shima City.
* '''Gochi Trail''': A pedestrian-only route starting near {{ill|Gochi Station|ja|五知駅|qq=|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in Shima City.
== References ==
{{reflist|qq=}}
== Further Reading ==
* Isobe Town History Compilation Committee, *Isobe Town History: Upper Volume*, 1997.
* Kawai Masatora, "Exploring the Origins of the Japanese Archipelago," *Geological News*, 1967.
* Toba City History Compilation Office, *Toba City History: Upper and Lower Volumes*, 1991.
* Hosoi Keiji, "Seihō Shimada and the Haiku Literary Movement," *Haiku Literature Quarterly*, 1996.
* Mie Prefecture Board of Education, *Historical Pathways of Ise: Asama-Toba Road and Others*, 1986.
